      "text": "# Poverty"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8a7b111008d8d38a",
      "text": "Information poverty and a lack of [[Requisite Variety]], that is diversity of expertise leads the centre to appoint specialist or [[Expert Help]]. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2f6bd4f654785bb7",
      "text": "Traditional approaches to how this help is appointed and recruitment often fails to satisfy the need to obtain the quality and diversity of information required to successfully manage operations, or represent the interests of the community."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "3da0100135ee84d4",
      "text": "# Defensiveness"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "547dc79d59b7d939",
      "text": "In the face of constant demands for communication, change, or action the centre has little choice, or perceives it has little choice, but to say no. It puts up defences."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a4ce68d26f99b648",
      "text": "Pragmatically this means putting in place filters or outright barriers to communication, or offers of support and advice from the periphery. This exacerbates the original problem in that the time and energy taken to construct these barriers, leaves even less time to address the informational needs of the organisation."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "947ef7ff6174eeaa",
      "text": "Additionally the defensiveness, while some times succeeding in shielding the culture and scarce time resources at the centre, will usually provoke a reaction from the periphery. This reaction often angry, more demanding, or sometimes disillusioned and recalcitrant, further leads to less available resources and information poverty at the centre."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "3617cd8b405f3ff9",
      "text": "# Arrogance"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "72394e498dadee27",
      "text": "A natural consequence of this defensiveness is to react to perceived criticisms from the periphery with the view, privately held or publicly declared that the periphery is unaware of the complex nature of the problems at the centre. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8563a18180d8f423",
      "text": "The centre is therefore led to believe that what is required is for the periphery to become more tolerant / \"educated\" with regard to the nature of the difficulties inherent to the organisational structure. Failing this the periphery should keep within its narrowly defined domain of expertise, and leave the centre to perform it's natural function."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "dfb38b45a17989b2",
      "text": "In a democratic hierarchy, this view is further justified because after all the centre has been elected, and is the only body with a right to organise wide-ranging or systemic activities."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "abb6ed01497f2352",
      "text": "These responses however natural are in essence arrogant. They do not respect the frailty, and inevitable blindness that their position in the centre entails. Natural human reactions to any challenges, compounded by the scarcity of time and resources experienced by the central team, leads naturally to a judgement that the fault lies with the other. The onus for change or learning is with the periphery."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "fdc5fa9c4482fbbe",
      "text": "# Failure to learn"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5f1aedf0cd62a05c",
      "text": "This defensiveness and arrogance, plus the lack of time and resources, and the constant demands for action, leads to an active refusal for the centre to learn - that is to take the time required to look at it's own inadequacies and limitations, and to put in place practices and learning models to address these."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fbc3e7752c71291a",
      "text": "A common response from the management team is to deny the nature of the problem, or at least to deprioritise the effort required to make structural changes needed. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "36d3b718024601f2",
      "text": "In particular a common response is to fail to look at and learn from the previous experience of similar organisational endeavours. The problem may not be present \"now\", so we can adapt and learn as and when the problem occurs. Confidence is placed within the good intentions of the team, and their willingness to adapt to situations as they turn up."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "90c77b507b4f2610",
      "text": "This amounts to nothing less than ostrich like behaviour. A cursory look at the recurrent nature of the problem, and the serious nature of its consequences, would lead to the clear conclusion that the only rational way to tackle the problem is to address it early and structurally. Prevention is better than cure."
    },
